  "nf_comparison": {
    "note": "NF class numbers grow roughly as sqrt(|disc|) / log(|disc|) for imaginary quadratic fields. Lattice class numbers show the opposite trend: higher dimension -> class_number concentrates at 1. This reflects Smith-Minkowski-Siegel mass formula: in high dim, most genera contain a single class.",
    "dim2_analogy": "dim=2 lattice class numbers = class numbers of binary quadratic forms = class numbers of imaginary quadratic orders. Direct correspondence via disc = -4*det(Gram)."
  },
  "verdict": "LMFDB lattice class numbers: dim=2 all cn=1 in dataset (1609 records, LMFDB stores one rep per genus). dim=3 is the rich dimension: n=36585, mean=15.5, median=13, max=56, only 2.6% have cn=1. dims 4-7 (n=1048) are 100% cn=1. High-dim singletons (dim=11-24) are famous lattices with cn>1 (Leech lattice dim=24 cn=24). dim=3 log(det) vs log(cn) correlation r=0.44: larger determinant -> larger class number. Parallel to NF: imaginary quadratic class numbers grow with discriminant."
}